{{Short description|American actor|bot=PearBOT 5}} {{Infobox person | name = David Corenswet | image = David_Corenswet_at_a_celebration_in_December_2019.jpg | caption = Corenswet in December 2019 | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1993|7|8}} | birth_place = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], U.S. | birth_name = David Packard Corenswet | education = [[Juilliard School]] ([[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]]) | occupation = Actor | yearsactive = 2011–present }} '''David Packard Corenswet''' (born July 8, 1993) is an American actor. After graduating from the [[Juilliard School]] in 2016, he began guest starring in television series, including ''[[House of Cards (American TV series)|House of Cards]]'' in 2018. He then starred in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[The Politician (TV series)|The Politician]]'' (2019–present) and ''[[Hollywood (miniseries)|Hollywood]]'' (2020), both of which were created by [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]].<ref>Gay, Verne, {{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/the-politician-review-1.36828954|title=''The Politician'': Uneven, but Entertaining|website=Newsday}} September 25, 2019.</ref><ref>Rose, Lacy, [https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/ryan-murphys-hollywood-meet-familiar-cast-netflixs-drama-1290997/item/darren-criss-ryan-murphy-frequent-stars-1291001 “Ryan Murphy’s ''Hollywood'': Meet the (Familiar) Cast of the Netflix Period Drama.”] ''The Hollywood Reporter''. April 22, 2020.</ref>
==Early life== Corenswet was raised in [[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].<ref>Myers, Owen, {{Cite web|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/directors-cut-david-corenswet/|title=Director's Cut: David Corenswet | V Magazine|website=vmagazine.com}} September 19, 2019.</ref> His father, John Corenswet,<ref>De Bertodano, Helene, [https://magazinec.com/culture/david-corenswets-bright-future-begins-in-hollywood/ “David Corenswet’s Bright Future Begins in ''Hollywood''.“] ''C Magazine''. April 30, 2020.</ref> was from a prominent Jewish family in [[New Orleans]],<ref>Ikes, Trey, [https://allstatesugarbowl.org/classic/sam-corenswet-a-lifetime-of-service/ “Sam Corenswet: A Lifetime of Service.”] ''Allstate Sugar Bowl Program, 2017''.</ref> and worked as a stage actor in New York City for many years<ref>Myers, Owen, {{Cite web|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/directors-cut-david-corenswet/|title=Director's Cut: David Corenswet | V Magazine|website=vmagazine.com}} September 19, 2019.</ref> before becoming a lawyer;<ref>Gardiner, Margaret, [https://youtube.com/qckDFU75lyI “David Corenswet, Jeremy Pope - Kim Kardashian, Met Ball, ''Hollywood''.”] Interview for the ''[[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]]''. April 20, 2020.</ref> his mother, Caroline Packard, is a lawyer who specializes in nonprofit organizational conflict resolution; his sister, Amy Packard Corenswet, is a 2020 graduate of UPenn law school.<ref>Gray, Ellen, [https://www.inquirer.com/entertainment/david-corenswet-interview-hollywood-the-politician-shipley-philly-20200529.html. “Philly’s David Corenswet Is Making It in Netflix’s ''Hollywood''.”] ''Philadelphia Inquirer''. May 29, 2020.</ref><ref>Hicklin, Aaron, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/24/style/david-corenswet-politican-ryan-murphy-hollywood.html “David Corenswet, a Breakout Star in ''The Politician'', Takes Flight.”] ''The New York Times''. January 24, 2020.</ref><ref>Zafar, Mishal, [https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/who-is-hollywood-star-david-corenswet-and-is-he-dating-anyone.html “Who Is ''Hollywood'' Star David Corenswet, and Is He Dating Anyone?”] ''Showbiz Cheatsheet''. May 1, 2020.</ref>
Corenswet's maternal grandfather is [[Edward Packard (writer)|Edward Packard]], creator of the ''[[Choose Your Own Adventure]]'' book concept and author of more than 50 books in the series.<ref>Andres, Tommy, & Tobin, Ariana, [https://www.marketplace.org/2014/04/11/how-choose-your-own-adventure-was-born/ “How ''Choose Your Own Adventure'' Was Born.”] ''[[Marketplace (radio program)|Marketplace]]'' ([[Minnesota Public Radio]]). April 11 2014.</ref><ref>Rosen, Jake, [https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/56160/brief-history-choose-your-own-adventure “A Brief History of ''Choose Your Own Adventure''.”] ''Mental Floss''. April 10, 2014.</ref> His maternal grandmother was a prominent [[Quakers |Quaker]] activist.<ref>[https://www.cpti.ws/memorials/MemorialRosaPackard.html “In Memory of Rosa Covington Packard.”] ''Conscience and Peace Tax International''. September, 2016.</ref>
Corenswet earned a bachelor of fine arts in drama in 2016 from the [[Juilliard School]] in [[New York City]].<ref>Myers, Owen, {{Cite web|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/directors-cut-david-corenswet/|title=Director's Cut: David Corenswet | V Magazine|website=vmagazine.com}} September 19, 2019.</ref><ref>Denninger, Lindsay, {{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/who-plays-river-on-the-politician-david-corenswet-is-even-funnier-irl-18721738|title=Who Plays River on ''The Politician''? David Corenswet Is Even Funnier IRL|website=Bustle}} September 26, 2019.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/tv-movies/a29264582/the-politician-david-corenswet-age-facts/|title=The Politician’s David Corenswet Has Appeared in Shows Like ''House of Cards''|first=Jonathan|last=Borge|date=September 27, 2019|website=Oprah Magazine}}</ref> He applied and was accepted to Juilliard while a freshman at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref> Zafar, Mishal, [https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/who-is-hollywood-star-david-corenswet-and-is-he-dating-anyone.html “Who Is ''Hollywood'' Star David Corenswet, and Is He Dating Anyone?”] ''Showbiz Cheatsheet''. May 1, 2020.</ref>
==Career== As a child actor, Corenswet appeared in the [[Arden Theatre Company (Philadelphia)|Arden Theatre Company]]'s 2002 production of [[Arthur Miller]]'s ''[[All My Sons]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_YYHkLehhuoC&pg=PA187&dq=%22David+Corenswet%22+-wikipedia&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiPhbiYwbDlAhXEtlkKHQ3rDWoQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=%22David+Corenswet%22+-wikipedia&f=false|title=Theatre World: 2002-2003|first=Ben|last=Hodges|date=November 27, 2004|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|via=Google Books}}</ref> the [[The Philadelphia Shakespeare Festival | Philadelphia Shakespeare Festival]]’s 2003 production of ''[[Macbeth]]'',<ref>Wallace, Debra, [https://www.suburbanlifemagazine.com/article/2420/The-Natural “The Natural: An Acting Career Seemed Fated for David Corenswet, Star of Netflix’s ''The Politician''.”] ''Suburban Life Magazine Philadelphia.'' November 2019.</ref> the [[Walnut Street Theatre]] Company's 2003 production of ''La Vie En Bleu'',<ref>Jones, Kenneth,[http://www.playbill.com/article/cast-picked-for-us-premiere-of-picasso-musical-la-vie-en-bleu-in-philly-sept-2-oct-19-com-114284 "Cast Picked for U.S. Premiere of Picasso Musical, ''La Vie En Bleu'', in Philly Sept. 2-Oct. 19"]. ''Playbill''. July 15, 2003.</ref><ref>Wallace, Debra, [https://www.suburbanlifemagazine.com/article/2420/The-Natural “The Natural: An Acting Career Seemed Fated for David Corenswet, Star of Netflix’s ''The Politician''.”] ''Suburban Life Magazine Philadelphia.'' November 2019.</ref> the [[People's Light and Theatre Company]]'s 2004 production of ''The Forgiving Harvest'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NyF9aBTDmj4C&pg=PA5&dq=%22David+Corenswet%22+-wikipedia&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjJrKC-v7DlAhVuzlkKHc6UDq0Q6AEwAXoECAMQAg#v=onepage&q=%22David+Corenswet%22+-wikipedia&f=false|title= ''The Forgiving Harvest: A Play in Two Acts''|first=Y.|last=York|date=October 27, 2005|publisher=Dramatic Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xdKnkj1qsocC&pg=PA244&dq=%22David+Corenswet%22+-wikipedia&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiPhbiYwbDlAhXEtlkKHQ3rDWoQ6AEwAnoECAMQAg#v=onepage&q=%22David+Corenswet%22+-wikipedia&f=false|title=Theatre World: 2003-2004. Vol. 60|first=John|last=Willis|date=April 21, 2006|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|via=Google Books}}</ref> and several other professional theater productions.<ref>[http://www.abouttheartists.com/artists/278718-david-corenswet “David Corenswet’s Professional Theater Credits, 2005-2013”] ''Abouttheartists.com''. Retrieved May 5, 2020.</ref>
His first film role was in ''Following Chase'' (2011), a Crossbow Studio production for which he also wrote the screenplay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crossbowstudio.com/films/following-chase/following-chase-cast-crew/|title=''Following Chase'' Cast & Crew|website=Crossbow Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref> He next co-wrote, produced, and starred in a two-season sketch-comedy web series, ''Moe & Jerryweather'' (2014-2016).<ref> Borge, Jonathan, & Nicolaou, Elena, [https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/tv-movies/a29264582/the-politician-david-corenswet-age-facts/, “Who Plays Jack Castello on ''Hollywood''? All About David Corenswet.”] ''Oprah Magazine''. April 30, 2020.</ref><ref> Corenswet, David, & Langdon, Adam, [https://vimeo.com/moeandjerry ''Moe and Jerryweather'' (2014-2016 sketch-comedy webseries).] ''Vimeo.'' Retrieved May 14, 2020.</ref>
In Corenswet’s first film role after graduating from Juilliard, he starred as Michael Lawson in ''[[Affairs of State (film)|Affairs of State]]'' (2018), a political thriller that had a limited release in theaters, then streamed on [[Amazon Prime Video]]. The film also stars [[Thora Birch]], [[Mimi Rogers]], and [[Adrian Grenier]]. Describing Corenswet’s character as "an ambitious but cash-strapped politico," the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called the film “engaging,” “well-acted,” and “refreshingly smart,” though “ungainly.”<ref>Murray, Noel, {{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mini-affairs-of-state-review-20180613-story.html|title=Review: Sex-Tinged Melodrama ''Affairs of State'' Mirrors Real Politics|date=June 13, 2018|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> [[Forbes|''Forbes'' magazine]] said of Corenswet’s performance in the role that he "has the right star-making combination of traditional good looks and a compelling deadpan voice that keeps you guessing...he's reminiscent of a younger [[Armie Hammer]]."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/lukethompson/2018/08/14/blu-ray-review-affairs-of-state-is-cheesy-fun-that-should-have-been-sleazier/|title=Blu-ray Review: ''Affairs of State'' Is Cheesy Fun That Should Have Been Sleazier|first=Luke Y.|last=Thompson|website=Forbes}} August 14, 2018.</ref>
Corenswet also appeared in guest-star roles on several TV series, including [[House of Cards (American TV series)|''House of Cards'']] (as the college flame of [[Robin Wright]]'s character, [[Claire Underwood]]), [[Elementary (TV series)|''Elementary'']], and [[Instinct (American TV series)|''Instinct'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/tv-movies/a29264582/the-politician-david-corenswet-age-facts/|title=The Politician’s David Corenswet Has Appeared in Shows Like House of Cards|first=Jonathan|last=Borge|date=September 27, 2019|website=Oprah Magazine}}</ref>
In ''[[The Politician (TV series)|The Politician]]'' (2019-present),<ref>Mohd, Sajid, [https://thedigitalwise.com/2020/03/22/the-politician-season-2-is-it-renewed-or-cancelled-know-every-details-here/ “''The Politician'' Season 2: Is It Renewed or Cancelled? Who Will Feature?”]. ''The Digital Wise''. March 22, 2020.</ref><ref>Wang, Jessica, [https://www.bustle.com/p/the-politician-season-2-will-still-premiere-this-summer-says-ryan-murphy-22858588 ''The Politician'' Season 2 Will Still Premiere This Summer, Says Ryan Murphy.”] ''Bustle.com''. April 29, 2020.</ref> he plays River Barkley, the lover and high-school political rival of Payton Hobart ([[Ben Platt (actor)|Ben Platt]]). [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|''Vanity Fair'' magazine]] described River as “the wealthy, sporty, straight-A student who is fluent in [[Mandarin Chinese]] and dates the prettiest and most popular girl...in school. But while his life looks perfect from the outside, he's also battling inner demons."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/07/ryan-murphy-the-politician-netflix-ben-platt|title= ''The Politician'': Ben Platt Previews Ryan Murphy’s Acerbic First Netflix Show|first=Paul|last=Chi|website=Vanity Fair}} July 17, 2019.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/tv/a29386391/who-is-david-corenswet-the-politician/|title=Everything You Need to Know About ''Politician'' Hottie David Corenswet|first=Leah|last=Thomas|date=October 7, 2019|website=Cosmopolitan}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucsdguardian.org/2019/10/19/tv-review-politician/|title=TV Review: ''The Politician''|first=Chloe|last=Esser|date=October 19, 2019}} ''[[UCSD Guardian]]''.</ref> Corenswet had to learn Mandarin Chinese for the role.<ref>Bernardini, Gabrielle, {{Cite web|url=https://www.distractify.com/p/david-corenswet|title=Who Plays River in Netflix's ''The Politician''? What to Know About Rising Star David Corenswet|website=Distractify}} September, 2019.</ref> Critics praised his performance, calling him “a real find,” with a “genuine screen presence,”<ref>Bullions, Matt, [https://saltlakefilmreview.com/2019/10/31/the-politician-is-inconsistent-yet-vastly-entertaining/ “''The Politician'' Can Be Inconsistent, But It’s Very Entertaining.”] ''Salt Lake Film Review''. October 31, 2019.</ref> who “radiated every time he was on the screen,” “charmed us with his [[Superman | Clark-Kent-like]] smile,” and “[made us] ache for him every time he teared up.”<ref>[https://whatculture.com/tv/the-politician-review-5-ups-3-downs?page=3. ''The Politician'' Review: Five Ups and Three Downs.] ''What Culture''. September 29, 2019.</ref>
Corenswet stars as Jack Castello<ref>Miller, Julie, [https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/04/inside-ryan-murphys-hollywood-a-revisionist-homage-to-golden-age-tinseltown “Inside Ryan Murphy’s ''Hollywood'', a Revisionist Homage to Golden Age of Tinseltown.”] ''Vanity Fair''. April 2, 2020.</ref> <ref>Bullions, Matt, [https://saltlakefilmreview.com/2020/06/09/hollywood-dazzles-thrills-and-imagines-a-better-world/ “''Hollywood'' Dazzles, Thrills, and Imagines a Better World.”] ''Salt Lake Film Review''. June 9, 2020.</ref> in ''[[Hollywood (miniseries)|Hollywood]]'' (2020), a Netflix limited series about the post-World War II film business in [[Los Angeles]], created by [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] and [[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]]. Corenswet is also an executive producer on the series.<ref>Andreeva, Nellie, & Petski, Denise, {{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/david-corenswet-ryan-murphy-hollywood-netflix-drama-series-the-politician-1202744640/|title=The Politician’s David Corenswet To Star In Ryan Murphy’s Netflix Series ''Hollywood'' |date=September 25, 2019}} ''Deadline Hollywood News''.</ref> He stars alongside [[Patti Lupone]], [[Dylan McDermott]], [[Darren Criss]], and [[Holland Taylor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/david-corenswet-appearing-in-another-ryan-murphy-series-for-netflix/vi-AAI4CQS|title=David Corenswet Appearing in Another Ryan Murphy Series For Netflix|website=www.msn.com}} September 30, 2019.</ref><ref>Lenker, Maureen Lee, [https://ew.com/tv/2019/11/26/breaking-big-the-politician-david-corenswet/ “Breaking Big: How ''The Politician''’s David Corenswet Became ''Hollywood'' Material,”] ''Entertainment Weekly''. November 26, 2019.</ref> ''[[Men’s Health]]'' magazine described Jack Castello as “a post-WWII veteran...a wide-eyed kid seeking fame....a ‘[[James Stewart |Jimmy Stewart]]’ everyman...looking for any path to a career in movies.” The magazine praised Corenswet’s performance as that of a “breakout lead” with “the on-screen charisma of a future star.”<ref>Romano, Evan,[https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a32321006/david-corenswet-interview-hollywood-netflix/ “David Corenswet Traveled to the 1940s for ''Hollywood''. He Could Be the Next Big Star in 2020.”] ''Men’s Health Magazine''. May 1, 2020.</ref> ''[[IndieWire]]'' called it “...another star-proving turn from David Corenswet.”<ref>Travers, Ben, [https://www.indiewire.com/2020/05/netflix-best-new-shows-may-2020-full-list-1202226732/ “Seven New Netflix Shows in May 2020, and the Best Reasons to Watch.”] ''Indiewire''. May 3, 2020.</ref>
